one of the benefit

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:06.830
is that we have a pretty
large inflexible fund family.

00:13:06.830 --> 00:13:11.020
And we want to expand our
topography uses in the product

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:14.710
and make it more purposeful
and more compelling.

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:17.520
So we apply more style,
style for the theme,

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:21.120
for the medium, for
action and so on,

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:23.260
and make it more appropriate.

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:25.490
And we want to give the
page more breathing room,

00:13:25.490 --> 00:13:27.770
feel less clutter
and complicated.

00:13:27.770 --> 00:13:30.290
And so we had a generous
amount of padding

00:13:30.290 --> 00:13:32.560
and we play with
alignment as well.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:35.630
So these will give the UI a
more fresh and modern and clean,

00:13:35.630 --> 00:13:38.120
and the text will be
more easier to read.

00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:42.600
So we also increased
the contrast

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:44.900
in adjusting the scale
of the typography

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:49.860
to make the hierarchy more
cleaner and easy to read.

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:51.940
And we explore also
overlaying typography

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:54.100
in content which can
be really powerful.

00:13:54.100 --> 00:13:56.600
And considering things
like legibility of the text

00:13:56.600 --> 00:14:00.080
without compromising the
image and the masses.

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:01.150
And then colors.

00:14:01.150 --> 00:14:03.545
Colors can be really
powerful in your design.

00:14:03.545 --> 00:14:05.670
And with material design,
we embrace it completely.

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:13.810
So we take advantage of these
beautiful new material design

00:14:13.810 --> 00:14:17.129
color palette, which
represent the brand colors.

00:14:17.129 --> 00:14:18.670
And we wanted to
apply it to our URI,

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:21.400
so we believe that
we wanted to make

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:23.420
the colors more
vivid and exciting.

00:14:23.420 --> 00:14:27.440
And so we started redefining
all the usage of our color

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:29.440
in the whole Play experience.

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:32.430
And we made the color
brighter and more vibrant

00:14:32.430 --> 00:14:35.470
to represent more the
Google Play brand.

00:14:35.470 --> 00:14:39.210
And also add a more
fresh and modern look.

00:14:39.210 --> 00:14:44.627
And there's also the functional
aspect of using color.

00:14:44.627 --> 00:14:45.710
You have a sense of place.

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:46.668
You know where you are.

00:14:46.668 --> 00:14:50.570
Or actions are more highlighted
and more easy to read.

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:52.290
We also play with
color extraction

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:56.150
which is a really important part
of material design guidelines.

00:14:56.150 --> 00:14:58.430
And you can see
how it works well

00:14:58.430 --> 00:15:01.435
in a service like Play
which is a media service.

00:15:04.190 --> 00:15:07.130
So This is a great example to
show you how much your design

00:15:07.130 --> 00:15:09.020
guidelines can be
flexible enough

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:10.820
to make your own color pallet.

00:15:10.820 --> 00:15:13.750
In fact, we extract
the color that we need

00:15:13.750 --> 00:15:17.000
and we make our
own color pallet.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:18.090
Imagery.

00:15:18.090 --> 00:15:21.300
When you think about Play, you
think about content, media.

00:15:21.300 --> 00:15:23.650
It's defined by its own content.

00:15:23.650 --> 00:15:26.740
Which, of course, rely
heavily on images.

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:28.270
So we always want it to be bold.

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:30.860
And we were already pretty bold
right now with the products.

00:15:30.860 --> 00:15:32.860
But we want to be
even more immersive

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:35.150
and represent the content
in all its beauty.

00:15:35.150 --> 00:15:38.350
And most importantly, we want to
create an emotional connection

00:15:38.350 --> 00:15:41.870
between the user
and the content.

00:15:41.870 --> 00:15:46.360
So we start developing
for different screen size,

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:49.970
and you can't imagine
how big and bold can

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:54.370
be the images in a larger
screen such as TV or a tablet.

00:15:54.370 --> 00:15:56.180
So the contents
speak for itself.

00:15:56.180 --> 00:16:00.820
And the contents are
real here on the page.

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:04.220
Of course we align other
things to material design,

00:16:04.220 --> 00:16:06.380
like the grid, the
layout, the metric,

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:10.109
and, of course,
iconography as well.

00:16:10.109 --> 00:16:12.650
So you can see that everything
has a consistent visual story.

00:16:12.650 --> 00:16:16.380
And the Play experience feel
like part of the same family.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:18.760
And this could be a
possible evolution

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:20.130
of however we use a language.

00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:23.010
You have material
design applied.

00:16:23.010 --> 00:16:25.410
So these were the three
areas as of our user language

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:27.700
that we did our first pass.

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:31.220
And for other problems such as
text editor app or a messaging

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:35.641
app, your starting point
can be totally different.

00:16:35.641 --> 00:16:37.140
But there's something
more important

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:38.940
that is missing
here that combined

00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:42.060
all these things together
and with interaction

00:16:42.060 --> 00:16:44.820
and actually make a truly
enchanting and magic

00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:48.549
experience, which is motion.

00:16:48.549 --> 00:16:50.340
One of the core aspects
of material design,

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:51.990
as you are already
probably know,

00:16:51.990 --> 00:16:57.110
is how can motion design
bring life into a product.

00:16:57.110 --> 00:16:59.140
We were really
excited about that.

00:16:59.140 --> 00:17:02.620
So the team and visual
designer were already

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:07.040
exploring all this stuff before
in an our early exploration.

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:09.154
So we were doing also
visual expiration

00:17:09.154 --> 00:17:11.740
and storyboard that
can represent motion

00:17:11.740 --> 00:17:15.640
and can be easily translated
into moving images.

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:18.480
So we started thinking
about how we can find a way

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:21.849
to tie all these things
together and thinking

00:17:21.849 --> 00:17:24.675
about how the user moves
through the experience

00:17:24.675 --> 00:17:26.990
and how to interact and
engage in the content.

00:17:26.990 --> 00:17:30.980
And the emotion that you
feel doing all of these.

00:17:30.980 --> 00:17:33.310
So we can apply motion
without a story.

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:35.352
And what is our motion story?

00:17:35.352 --> 00:17:36.435
It's been straightforward.

00:17:36.435 --> 00:17:39.100
It is a typical story.

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:41.580
There is a starting
point where in the motion

00:17:41.580 --> 00:17:47.190
world can be translated like
the user is guide to the UI

00:17:47.190 --> 00:17:49.980
and how things appear
and how things load.

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:54.020
And then there is a medial
stage where the action happened

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:57.990
and what's the feeling and
emotion that the user is

00:17:57.990 --> 00:17:59.530
feeling at the moment.

00:17:59.530 --> 00:18:02.440
And then there is the end
where the animation is actually

00:18:02.440 --> 00:18:03.240
resolving.

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:08.820
So where user lands into the
page after the animation.

00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:11.960
So as Nate mentioned before,
we define hero screen,

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:13.860
but also we define
hero moments that

00:18:13.860 --> 00:18:16.250
were guide all these
explorations that you're

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:19.280
going to see today,
and things like

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:22.980
how the object move in the
space, how the object appears

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:26.880
or transitions, and
most importantly, create

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:30.100
meaningful motion that
can connect emotionally

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:33.174
and can make you feel something.

00:18:33.174 --> 00:18:35.090
So taking on the latest
structures [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:37.110
was talking about
before, you can already

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:39.000
see that one sees emotion.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.480
You understand where the objects
are and how they could move

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:46.030
and potentially how you
can interact with them.

00:18:46.030 --> 00:18:48.600
And the parallax effect,
not just the flavor

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:51.100
or just the fashion things that
everyone is using right now.

00:18:51.100 --> 00:18:54.140
But it's actually
purposeful for the motion.

00:18:54.140 --> 00:18:55.920
You understand where
the objects are

00:18:55.920 --> 00:18:58.170
and how you can
interact with them.

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:02.450
Blocking out animation.

00:19:02.450 --> 00:19:06.600
Once we were starting doing
this prototype and exploration,

00:19:06.600 --> 00:19:09.560
it was really important to
get the animation right.

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:13.070
So we reduce completely, the
level of detail and thinking

00:19:13.070 --> 00:19:16.880
blocks, and focus only on the
motion and the actual sense

00:19:16.880 --> 00:19:19.450
of the motion and
bring the movement

00:19:19.450 --> 00:19:21.580
as natural as possible.

00:19:21.580 --> 00:19:24.220
So don't worry about around the
corner, or pixel perfect stuff

00:19:24.220 --> 00:19:27.350
in this time.

00:19:27.350 --> 00:19:30.060
So this is our early
exploration where

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:33.750
we wanted to show how
things load in the page.

00:19:33.750 --> 00:19:35.530
But we weren't quite
happy with that

00:19:35.530 --> 00:19:37.020
because there is
too much going on.

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:40.640
There is too much tilting
the card too fast.

00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:43.360
And it was an
overwhelming experience.

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:46.460
User will actually too
distracted from the movement.

00:19:46.460 --> 00:19:50.210
So we simplify the transition
and make it more simple,

00:19:50.210 --> 00:19:52.690
and guide the user
attention and focus

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:58.190
through the actual important
thing, which is the content.

00:19:58.190 --> 00:20:00.310
So we explore also
how content loads

00:20:00.310 --> 00:20:03.030
when there is a measured
change in the screen layout.

00:20:03.030 --> 00:20:05.235
Like in this case, you
talk to a collection,

00:20:05.235 --> 00:20:07.390
and you go into
the detail phase.

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:11.200
And what is very interesting
here is with material design,

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:14.490
you have a feeling that you
have full control of the UI,

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:16.910
and that you
actually almost paint

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:18.625
the screen with you finger.

00:20:21.530 --> 00:20:23.650
And here's another
example of how

00:20:23.650 --> 00:20:28.180
things can load from a place
into a totally different place.

00:20:28.180 --> 00:20:32.420
Like here, I'm in
a home home phase,

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:36.060
and then I'm going
to a detail page.

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:38.580
And here, example of how we
could interact with objects

00:20:38.580 --> 00:20:39.830
like opening and closing.

00:20:39.830 --> 00:20:42.700
In this case, in Newsstand,
you're opening the object

00:20:42.700 --> 00:20:43.610
and the card expands.

00:20:43.610 --> 00:20:46.780
And it goes S to S until
it gets full screen,

00:20:46.780 --> 00:20:51.460
and you see the real
content in all its beauty.

00:20:51.460 --> 00:20:55.320
So this transition is
especially important

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:58.500
because you have a special sense
of where things are removed.

00:20:58.500 --> 00:21:00.250
And in this case, the
most important thing

00:21:00.250 --> 00:21:03.284
is the backward transition, with
if we had to tell the story,

00:21:03.284 --> 00:21:04.700
you have to tell
a complete story.

00:21:04.700 --> 00:21:10.612
So you want also to
[INAUDIBLE] and key experience

00:21:10.612 --> 00:21:11.570
once you're going back.

00:21:11.570 --> 00:21:13.760
So backward
transition for us was

00:21:13.760 --> 00:21:16.579
crucial as any other key motion.

00:21:16.579 --> 00:21:18.620
Of course, we were doing
all of this motion study

00:21:18.620 --> 00:21:22.870
with engineering and each
array team and reviewing.

00:21:22.870 --> 00:21:26.790
But Will will go in
depth about that.

00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:30.660
Again, opening and closing
elements is fast using place.

00:21:30.660 --> 00:21:32.820
The card expand and contract.

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:33.969
The object is marked.

00:21:33.969 --> 00:21:36.385
He knows where he comes from,
and he knows where he lands.

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:40.620
And of course, detailed matter.

00:21:40.620 --> 00:21:43.000
So we look at
purposeful animation

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:47.330
and enhance the overall
experience with little touches.

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:50.460
Like in this case,
the loading spinner.

00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:52.760
You also have a chance
to brand these things,

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:56.330
so we were trying to
express the product that we

00:21:56.330 --> 00:22:00.110
were showing-- in
this case, movies.

00:22:00.110 --> 00:22:03.790
So this will give the user
an engagement, and also

00:22:03.790 --> 00:22:07.850
a little bit of surprise
and curiosity to the UI.

00:22:07.850 --> 00:22:10.870
Again, details are
important, so an animation

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:13.820
that could be static
and pretty boring,

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:18.570
we actually trying to make a
storytelling aspect into it.

00:22:18.570 --> 00:22:22.060
So like the downloading arrow.

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:24.770
So here, this is
an example of how

00:22:24.770 --> 00:22:27.399
can be the potential
complete story once you

00:22:27.399 --> 00:22:28.815
combine all these
pieces together.

00:22:33.730 --> 00:22:35.770
So these are our here moments.

00:22:35.770 --> 00:22:37.390
Every half has their own one.

00:22:37.390 --> 00:22:40.960
So it is up to you
to define which one.

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:42.460
So this is just
part of the magic.

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:44.940
This is mean nothing
without the actual someone

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:46.360
that can make it real.

00:22:46.360 --> 00:22:48.810
And as Nathan was
mentioning before,

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:51.200
it was that effort of
the team working together

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:53.220
with the engineering
product researcher.

00:22:53.220 --> 00:22:57.550
And this time, we'll have
Will talking about in detail

00:22:57.550 --> 00:23:00.250
how we actually
did these things.

00:23:00.250 --> 00:23:03.242
Thank you.

00:23:03.242 --> 00:23:04.450
WILL KIEFER: Thank you Teddy.

00:23:04.450 --> 00:23:06.770
So I'm going to give you
guys a little glimpse

00:23:06.770 --> 00:23:09.530
into the engineering
process, and what

00:23:09.530 --> 00:23:12.030
was going on throughout
all this on the engineering

00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:12.990
side of things.

00:23:12.990 --> 00:23:16.850
And the key takeaway is
really that it was the same.

00:23:16.850 --> 00:23:19.650
We were working in
parallel and collaborating

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:22.821
sort of simultaneously
back and forth.

00:23:22.821 --> 00:23:24.570
And one of the early
things Nate mentioned

00:23:24.570 --> 00:23:27.170
is the early stage of
identifying your opportunities,

00:23:27.170 --> 00:23:27.690
right?

00:23:27.690 --> 00:23:29.280
I'm really lucky,
because I actually

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:32.990
work on both UX frameworks
and on the Play suite apps.

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:35.250
And so I kind of get
to wear both hats,

00:23:35.250 --> 00:23:38.730
and there are opportunities
in both of these places.

00:23:38.730 --> 00:23:41.210
So the core tenant
from the framework side

00:23:41.210 --> 00:23:42.970
of things, the core
opportunity there

00:23:42.970 --> 00:23:47.080
was to make it really
easy for your apps.

00:23:47.080 --> 00:23:52.110
We basically wanted to bake the
material DNA into the framework

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:56.010
so that that stuff just
comes along with your apps,

00:23:56.010 --> 00:23:58.090
and life is easy,
and you can focus

00:23:58.090 --> 00:24:03.610
on making the subtlety that
is appropriate for your app.

00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:07.160
So things like cards are
first class citizens now.

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:09.780
So you have consistency
across your cards in your app,

00:24:09.780 --> 00:24:12.530
across the system, the
notification, the system UI,

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:15.040
and it feels like
part of one family.

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:20.210
And there's elevation and
layering for your hero images,

00:24:20.210 --> 00:24:21.690
or your hero content.

00:24:21.690 --> 00:24:24.860
And then shadows, for maybe you
have custom shadows for content

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:27.720
that doesn't quite fit in
what the framework provides.

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:29.700
That's all there.

00:24:29.700 --> 00:24:31.860
Complex layouts are
now much easier.

00:24:31.860 --> 00:24:34.390
Everyone knows that,
design and engineering

00:24:34.390 --> 00:24:36.350
knows that list
view is very arduous

00:24:36.350 --> 00:24:38.140
to do some complex things.

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:40.120
So now you have
actual proper support

00:24:40.120 --> 00:24:43.540
both in L and in the compat
library with recycler view

00:24:43.540 --> 00:24:47.580
to make layouts that are
appropriate for your content.

00:24:47.580 --> 00:24:50.600
And actual support for animating
things in and animating things

00:24:50.600 --> 00:24:52.280
out.

00:24:52.280 --> 00:24:53.120
So it's really nice.

00:24:53.120 --> 00:24:54.536
And actually, my
personal favorite

00:24:54.536 --> 00:24:57.300
is the suite of API's
around scene transitions.

00:24:57.300 --> 00:25:02.400
This opens up a whole new
category of story and design

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:05.420
for your app that just basically
wasn't possible before.

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:09.420
And scene transitions are how
you're app or your activity

00:25:09.420 --> 00:25:12.130
animates in and then animates
out when it's disappearing.

00:25:12.130 --> 00:25:15.500
And this is into your app, or
across activities in your app,

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:17.090
or even between applications.

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:18.910
It's really pretty powerful.

00:25:18.910 --> 00:25:22.080
If you want to dig into some
of the things, some of this

00:25:22.080 --> 00:25:25.160
a little deeper, yesterday's
"What's New in Android" talk

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:28.590
is on video, is a great
whirlwind tour of everything.

00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:30.090
And then actually
right now, there's

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:32.717
a talk on material
science where they dig in.

00:25:32.717 --> 00:25:33.800
You can catch it on video.

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:35.787
And I think at 2:00 PM,
there's another talk

00:25:35.787 --> 00:25:37.620
where they're going to
walk through actually

00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:40.140
building material witness.

00:25:40.140 --> 00:25:43.110
Building an actual android
app with all this stuff.

00:25:43.110 --> 00:25:45.610
So that's a little bit of the
opportunities on the framework

00:25:45.610 --> 00:25:46.109
side.

00:25:46.109 --> 00:25:48.830
And so apps have their own
sort of personal opportunities.

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:51.891
Nate mentioned what Play
was looking at early on.

00:25:51.891 --> 00:25:53.390
Your apps may have
different things,

00:25:53.390 --> 00:25:57.690
but the other opportunities
to leverage the framework.

