But it's not actually very
rigid in your app structure.

00:26:16.570 --> 00:26:19.280
There's actually a lot of
flexibility in the system

00:26:19.280 --> 00:26:21.800
to make an app that
fits your content,

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:25.080
fits your structure,
fits what you want to do.

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:29.680
And so earlier, Teddy
alluded to the structure

00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:31.140
that Play was developing.

00:26:31.140 --> 00:26:33.280
And this didn't just
sort of come overnight,

00:26:33.280 --> 00:26:36.130
and get thrown over the wall
from design to engineering.

00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:39.500
This is a really good example
where we're working together

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:41.520
in parallel and
collaborating here.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:43.250
So I'm going to
share little vignette

00:26:43.250 --> 00:26:47.960
of an actual true story
of Play Newsstand,

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:50.300
and how that was happening.

00:26:50.300 --> 00:26:55.310
So early on, I saw some amazing
blue sky sort of moments.

00:26:55.310 --> 00:26:58.116
Visual mocks in motion
design and stuff.

00:26:58.116 --> 00:26:59.740
So I just went and
started prototyping.

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:02.870
And so everything you see here
is actual random prototypes

00:27:02.870 --> 00:27:06.730
from this time off my laptop.

00:27:06.730 --> 00:27:08.424
And I worked at it.

00:27:08.424 --> 00:27:09.840
I did a whole bunch
of iterations.

00:27:09.840 --> 00:27:10.381
I may builds.

00:27:10.381 --> 00:27:11.970
And I just was not happy.

00:27:11.970 --> 00:27:15.230
There were a couple
issues that came up

00:27:15.230 --> 00:27:17.410
when actually implementing
it that were really,

00:27:17.410 --> 00:27:19.780
I felt like we were going
to have to start over, take

00:27:19.780 --> 00:27:20.600
a new direction.

00:27:20.600 --> 00:27:26.030
There was issues with tabs and
having layers actually split

00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:29.409
when we scroll, and trying to
blend these different layers

00:27:29.409 --> 00:27:29.950
and parallax.

00:27:29.950 --> 00:27:33.620
And it's they're subtle
issues, but they were there.

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:38.320
And so basically, I was
giving daily builds.

00:27:38.320 --> 00:27:39.950
And one day I thought, oh man.

00:27:39.950 --> 00:27:40.380
OK, we're going to
have to start over.

00:27:40.380 --> 00:27:41.330
So I turned it off.

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:42.871
I reverted it, and
the next day, they

00:27:42.871 --> 00:27:46.530
would build, like went back to
a sort of a previous iteration.

00:27:46.530 --> 00:27:49.610
And a designer, the legendary
Marco, came up to me that day

00:27:49.610 --> 00:27:50.450
and was like, hey.

00:27:50.450 --> 00:27:51.550
Where did that go?

00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:52.800
This was awesome, I loved it.

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:53.425
And I said, oh.

00:27:53.425 --> 00:27:56.440
Well, obviously, it can't work
because of engineering reason

00:27:56.440 --> 00:27:58.950
A, B, C. And he
said, no, no, no.

00:27:58.950 --> 00:28:00.580
We can do this.

00:28:00.580 --> 00:28:02.890
Let's iterate, let's
solve those problems.

00:28:02.890 --> 00:28:05.605
And so we ended up
coming to a place--

00:28:05.605 --> 00:28:07.980
this is sort of the next stage
where we're like, oh yeah.

00:28:07.980 --> 00:28:08.896
It's actually working.

00:28:08.896 --> 00:28:12.009
This is, I think we can
pursue this structure.

00:28:12.009 --> 00:28:13.800
And this would not have
happened had we not

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:17.530
actually been prototyping
and iterating together.

00:28:17.530 --> 00:28:19.260
Having people live
with prototypes,

00:28:19.260 --> 00:28:22.360
even if they're very
rough and not quite right,

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:24.527
really lets you know if
the structure's going

00:28:24.527 --> 00:28:26.110
to work because
you're living with it.

00:28:26.110 --> 00:28:28.262
You can see what works,
what doesn't work.

00:28:28.262 --> 00:28:29.720
And so this is like
the next stage.

00:28:29.720 --> 00:28:32.290
We're getting a little bit
closer, and feeling like yes.

00:28:32.290 --> 00:28:33.581
We could pursue this structure.

00:28:33.581 --> 00:28:35.430
And once we got there,
then the whole sort

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:39.740
of rest of the pieces of the
app started to fall into place,

00:28:39.740 --> 00:28:44.180
and become a cohesive
story around this.

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:46.400
So that's a little
glimpse of the structure.

00:28:46.400 --> 00:28:49.410
Iterating in conjunction with
each other, living with it,

00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:53.220
and solving the structure
early on with prototypes

00:28:53.220 --> 00:28:55.930
to basically prove out the
technical feasibility of

00:28:55.930 --> 00:28:57.510
is that going to work?

00:28:57.510 --> 00:29:00.490
And you'll notice I showed
some iOS footage there.

00:29:00.490 --> 00:29:03.780
And Play is a cross
platform product.

00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:06.750
So this was going up, we were
firing on all cylinders, web,

00:29:06.750 --> 00:29:10.137
iOS, and Android, because the
challenges on each platform

00:29:10.137 --> 00:29:11.720
are going to be a
little bit different

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:13.720
and the interaction models
can be a little bit different.

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:15.511
And so it's really
important that if you're

00:29:15.511 --> 00:29:18.200
doing cross product
work, that you're

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:20.420
kind of repeating this
process in parallel

00:29:20.420 --> 00:29:23.120
across the different platforms.

00:29:23.120 --> 00:29:26.059
So the final piece
is story, and Teddy

00:29:26.059 --> 00:29:27.350
talked about this a little bit.

00:29:27.350 --> 00:29:28.225
And so what is story?

00:29:28.225 --> 00:29:30.370
It's basically connecting
these hero moments

00:29:30.370 --> 00:29:33.590
that you've defined for your
app using motion design,

00:29:33.590 --> 00:29:35.040
and using animation.

00:29:35.040 --> 00:29:37.720
And this animation is
not actually fluff.

00:29:37.720 --> 00:29:39.050
It's not eye candy.

00:29:39.050 --> 00:29:40.660
It's very purposeful.

00:29:40.660 --> 00:29:45.510
So when a user touches on a
card with an image and a title,

00:29:45.510 --> 00:29:47.800
and that image and
title stays on screen,

00:29:47.800 --> 00:29:52.240
transitions into place, and
supporting content and details

00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:55.580
appear to basically
supplement it.

00:29:55.580 --> 00:29:57.940
There are fewer pixels
moving on the screen.

00:29:57.940 --> 00:29:59.610
And with your pixels
moving, there's

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:03.520
actually less cognitive
overhead for your user.

00:30:03.520 --> 00:30:07.000
If it's an abrupt transition,
and everything changes at once

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:08.750
there's a lot more
cognitive overhead.

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:11.302
The user has to sort
of rescan everything,

00:30:11.302 --> 00:30:13.510
and reacquaint themselves
with where everything went.

00:30:13.510 --> 00:30:16.830
So this is very,
very purposeful.

00:30:16.830 --> 00:30:18.330
And that doesn't
mean everything has

00:30:18.330 --> 00:30:21.140
to be completely
smooth everywhere.

00:30:21.140 --> 00:30:25.340
There can be abrupt changes
just like in novels, and film,

00:30:25.340 --> 00:30:25.850
and music.

00:30:25.850 --> 00:30:29.660
There can be abrupt changes,
but they're purposeful.

00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:33.200
They're there for a reason.

00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:35.530
And so we looked at
Newsstand and we said, OK.

00:30:35.530 --> 00:30:38.150
What's one of our really
common transitions that now we

00:30:38.150 --> 00:30:40.050
can leverage this opportunity?

00:30:40.050 --> 00:30:43.950
And so collections of cards of
articles to the actual article

00:30:43.950 --> 00:30:44.450
themselves.

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:47.040
And you saw some of the motion
studies on this earlier.

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:48.570
This was a great
opportunity for us.

00:30:48.570 --> 00:30:52.470
And how did engineering actually
tackle this at the same time

00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:54.714
that the motion designers
were working on it?

00:30:54.714 --> 00:30:55.880
We used the same techniques.

00:30:55.880 --> 00:30:56.830
We use Block-it.

00:30:56.830 --> 00:31:00.110
Here's a random, early
prototype of just getting

00:31:00.110 --> 00:31:03.410
the blocks in place, and
giving the designers knobs

00:31:03.410 --> 00:31:06.320
to tweak like live on
the device to adjust

00:31:06.320 --> 00:31:09.350
timings and curves,
and all sorts of stuff

00:31:09.350 --> 00:31:11.100
so that they get really
immediate feedback

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:12.220
to feel what's working.

00:31:12.220 --> 00:31:16.210
Because when it's in your hand,
it just changes everything.

00:31:16.210 --> 00:31:19.360
Here's another example
in tablet where

00:31:19.360 --> 00:31:21.240
I slowed the entire
animation down.

00:31:21.240 --> 00:31:23.580
I used a big, bright,
red debug color

00:31:23.580 --> 00:31:26.050
just so I could really
focus on what was going on.

00:31:26.050 --> 00:31:28.410
And here, it turned out
that this was not right.

00:31:28.410 --> 00:31:31.610
You'll see the right edge, it's
the right edge of the tablet

00:31:31.610 --> 00:31:33.260
before the left side does.

00:31:33.260 --> 00:31:34.540
And it wasn't quite right.

00:31:34.540 --> 00:31:35.290
It wasn't working.

00:31:35.290 --> 00:31:37.530
So we iterated, and we adjusted.

00:31:37.530 --> 00:31:39.720
And you wouldn't really
notice that if you just

00:31:39.720 --> 00:31:41.860
put in the final
sort of transition

00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:44.571
without the color and
stuff, because it might just

00:31:44.571 --> 00:31:45.820
look pretty good in our right.

00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:48.278
But really slowing it down and
getting those details right.

00:31:48.278 --> 00:31:52.060
And so blocking is actually
very helpful on an engineering

00:31:52.060 --> 00:31:52.780
prospective.

00:31:52.780 --> 00:31:55.113
And so when you start putting
all these things together,

00:31:55.113 --> 00:31:59.650
you get this motion story
without these rough edges.

00:31:59.650 --> 00:32:01.950
And everything you do
and touch with the screen

00:32:01.950 --> 00:32:04.810
is purposeful and interactive.

00:32:04.810 --> 00:32:07.270
And it's important here
that these early prototypes,

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:08.447
the level of details high.

00:32:08.447 --> 00:32:09.280
This is not perfect.

00:32:09.280 --> 00:32:12.920
There's a lot of bugs, there's
a lot of weird color and issues.

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:17.130
But the important part is
that at a granular level,

00:32:17.130 --> 00:32:18.140
it's where you're going.

00:32:18.140 --> 00:32:21.460
And you live with it, and
you see if it's working.

00:32:21.460 --> 00:32:23.920
So that's a little
bit about Story.

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:26.120
And finally, I just wanted
to basically highlight

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:29.710
two sort of key takeaways
from our talk today.

00:32:29.710 --> 00:32:31.390
And one is this idea
that Nate mentioned

00:32:31.390 --> 00:32:34.760
of institutional
advocacy for design.

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:37.640
If everybody is involved
in design, than everybody

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:39.880
feels a bit of ownership
over that design.

00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:42.440
And if everyone feels
ownership of that design,

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:44.420
then everyone is
invested in it, and you

00:32:44.420 --> 00:32:46.330
get much better results.

00:32:46.330 --> 00:32:51.150
We have engineering product and
design all working together.

00:32:51.150 --> 00:32:51.840
And this scales.

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:56.150
This scales from a one person
indie dev to a big company.

00:32:56.150 --> 00:32:58.410
Design advocacy applies
in both situations.

00:32:58.410 --> 00:33:00.640
And arguably, it's
even more important

00:33:00.640 --> 00:33:02.690
when your team is much
bigger, because it's

00:33:02.690 --> 00:33:05.560
easier to sort of start
throwing things over the wall.

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:09.190
And you don't get quite
as good results that way.

00:33:09.190 --> 00:33:12.880
And the last point is
leveraging your opportunity.

00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:15.820
This is basically finding
those hero moments,

00:33:15.820 --> 00:33:17.500
finding of the parts
of your app you

00:33:17.500 --> 00:33:19.625
want to improve with the
parts of your app you want

00:33:19.625 --> 00:33:21.830
to highlight, and building
around those first.

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:25.530
Build blue skies, building
really nice mocks,

00:33:25.530 --> 00:33:28.720
and working out from there using
those to define your structure,

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:30.540
or refine your
structure if you already

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:32.830
feel very happy
with what you have.

00:33:32.830 --> 00:33:35.420
And then, prototyping early.

00:33:35.420 --> 00:33:38.060
Building that stuff, living
with it to see if it's working.

00:33:38.060 --> 00:33:40.820
And then connecting those
dots using the motion study

00:33:40.820 --> 00:33:42.720
in the story that
you want for the app.

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:44.730
And this is just
really fantastic,

00:33:44.730 --> 00:33:47.640
because material design
gives you these tools

00:33:47.640 --> 00:33:52.060
to basically connect all
this together and improve

00:33:52.060 --> 00:33:53.350
how everything works.

00:33:53.350 --> 00:33:55.830
So thank you for coming out
and by letting us give you

