00:37:49.482 --> 00:37:50.440
can just work together.

00:37:50.440 --> 00:37:54.270
Like literally, that moment
of just collaborating and just

00:37:54.270 --> 00:37:57.930
brainstorming, involving
each other in that part

00:37:57.930 --> 00:37:58.580
is really nice.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:38:01.040
Because then you're
on board together.

00:38:01.040 --> 00:38:03.480
That was really good in the
early days of Newsstand.

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:06.860
We got a couple engineers and
a couple designers in a room

00:38:06.860 --> 00:38:09.210
with basically where do
we want to be in 10 years?

00:38:09.210 --> 00:38:10.610
And where do we want
to be in five years?

00:38:10.610 --> 00:38:11.485
And just work it out.

00:38:11.485 --> 00:38:14.160
And then you feel like
you're on the same team.

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:17.700
So then you both have
ownership over it.

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:20.520
So it's easier to drive back
just from the bottom layer too.

00:38:24.469 --> 00:38:25.010
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:38:25.010 --> 00:38:25.962
WILL KIEFER: Oh, here.

00:38:25.962 --> 00:38:27.160
AUDIENCE: Hey, I'm Prishan.

00:38:27.160 --> 00:38:30.020
I run a small app company.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.739
One point of contention
we have is basically

00:38:32.739 --> 00:38:34.405
when to do the handover
from engineering

00:38:34.405 --> 00:38:35.650
to design, essentially.

00:38:35.650 --> 00:38:38.090
So my designer come up with
big, [INAUDIBLE] feature.

00:38:38.090 --> 00:38:40.360
My designer come up
with this beautiful UI

00:38:40.360 --> 00:38:41.950
layout and workflow.

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:43.610
And then you first
thing they say

00:38:43.610 --> 00:38:45.850
that this is not a
standard UI component.

00:38:45.850 --> 00:38:48.500
You should think in terms
of standard UI components

00:38:48.500 --> 00:38:49.850
available.

00:38:49.850 --> 00:38:53.240
And also when
standardization, A,

00:38:53.240 --> 00:38:55.180
do you encourage using
only the standard UI

00:38:55.180 --> 00:38:57.420
component because
user are familiar

00:38:57.420 --> 00:39:01.940
and there's less learning curve,
and when to empower design?

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:03.619
How do you make the decision?

00:39:03.619 --> 00:39:04.410
NATHAN STRUE: Sure.

00:39:04.410 --> 00:39:08.800
No, that's a very good question,
and I think super relevant.

00:39:08.800 --> 00:39:13.930
I think there's a lot of factors
that go into that hand off.

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:19.257
I mean, I think it depends the
competency of your designers

00:39:19.257 --> 00:39:20.840
and how familiar
they are with working

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:22.330
with framework components.

00:39:22.330 --> 00:39:25.490
And as Will was talking about,
it's that collaboration.

00:39:25.490 --> 00:39:31.330
So if there are designers that
aren't fully aware of what

00:39:31.330 --> 00:39:34.200
the suite of a
framework can offer,

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:37.250
it's really good to try
to bring them up to speed.

00:39:37.250 --> 00:39:40.940
And also going back to how we
were discussing opportunity,

00:39:40.940 --> 00:39:43.520
it's like where do you get
the most value, the most

00:39:43.520 --> 00:39:46.840
bang for your buck in
going a custom route?

00:39:46.840 --> 00:39:50.140
Now for certain
experiences, taking

00:39:50.140 --> 00:39:53.260
what the framework offers you
with minor changes, things that

00:39:53.260 --> 00:39:57.160
are easy to do in code, that can
make a big difference in design

00:39:57.160 --> 00:40:01.040
like changing font scaling,
are changing color palates,

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:03.170
changing background assets.

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:04.850
These things are
relatively cheap ways

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:06.290
that still leverage
the framework,

00:40:06.290 --> 00:40:10.380
but can give you a very
different look and feel.

00:40:10.380 --> 00:40:13.880
But it's also about when is
it appropriate to override

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:17.010
the framework or do
something custom?

00:40:17.010 --> 00:40:20.810
And I think that decision
comes from working together

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:23.310
as a team, and determining
whether or not it's worth

00:40:23.310 --> 00:40:24.650
the engineering investment.

00:40:24.650 --> 00:40:26.150
Is the payoff going
to be big enough

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:29.840
on undoing a
component in custom?

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:32.050
As an example in
Play, maybe we don't

00:40:32.050 --> 00:40:36.310
want to take the
platform scrubber bar,

00:40:36.310 --> 00:40:38.310
because we want to bring
something more branded

00:40:38.310 --> 00:40:40.260
or something that's
differentiated.

00:40:40.260 --> 00:40:41.945
And for us maybe,
that's a big win.

00:40:41.945 --> 00:40:43.570
I'm not saying that's
what we're doing,

00:40:43.570 --> 00:40:46.757
but that could be an example
of how you address that.

00:40:46.757 --> 00:40:48.840
WILL KIEFER: And from the
engineering perspective,

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:52.470
I'd say what's great
about material design is

00:40:52.470 --> 00:40:56.680
it's sort of like a higher level
philosophy that's not like, use

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:57.310
this button.

00:40:57.310 --> 00:40:58.330
Use this thing.

00:40:58.330 --> 00:41:00.427
It's like, here are
the guidelines and here

00:41:00.427 --> 00:41:01.760
the red lines, and these things.

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:04.100
And so actually, the compat
library and the framework

00:41:04.100 --> 00:41:07.220
are in some ways, much
more flexible to achieve

00:41:07.220 --> 00:41:09.569
what previously might
have been a lot more

00:41:09.569 --> 00:41:10.485
of a custom component.

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:18.360
AUDIENCE: So between prototyping
with After Effects or something

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:21.880
more interactive like
Quartz or HTML, when

00:41:21.880 --> 00:41:25.200
you see that payoff
in going interactive,

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:27.610
and what goes into
that decision making.

00:41:27.610 --> 00:41:29.430
Is it just the skill
sets on the team,

00:41:29.430 --> 00:41:34.540
or is there some sort
of thought process?

00:41:34.540 --> 00:41:37.020
NATHAN STRUE: Great question.

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:40.500
We would advocate for
getting it in people's hands

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:41.580
as quickly as possible.

00:41:41.580 --> 00:41:45.600
I mean, even literally if
it's sketches on paper that

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:49.430
are captured and broken up
into the variety of tools that

00:41:49.430 --> 00:41:52.950
are available for doing quick,
iterative, rapid prototyping

00:41:52.950 --> 00:41:55.690
on device.

00:41:55.690 --> 00:41:59.160
We live in a world where
everything is interactive,

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:04.010
and statics can't capture how
something is going to feel.

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:07.060
And so we in general,
advocate for trying

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:10.270
to do that as quickly as
possible with any tool that

00:42:10.270 --> 00:42:11.210
works.

00:42:11.210 --> 00:42:14.160
And you can continue to refine
and iterate, and develop,

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:16.400
and polish as you're going.

00:42:16.400 --> 00:42:18.970
And that tool set
can adapt depending

00:42:18.970 --> 00:42:20.480
on what your needs are.

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:22.206
But the sooner you
can start playing

00:42:22.206 --> 00:42:23.330
with something, the better.

00:42:23.330 --> 00:42:25.204
TADDEO ZACCHINI: Yeah,
it's a parallel track.

00:42:25.204 --> 00:42:27.910
I mean maybe the
motion designer will

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:32.640
start designing the motion,
and then the first draft

00:42:32.640 --> 00:42:34.470
will get in the
prototype, and then

00:42:34.470 --> 00:42:36.074
we figure out what we could do.

00:42:36.074 --> 00:42:37.740
And then production
design will go ahead

00:42:37.740 --> 00:42:38.900
and do all the pixel perfecting.

00:42:38.900 --> 00:42:40.920
Meanwhile, the engineering
will fix the motion.

00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:44.330
I mean, it's a collaboration.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:47.010
WILL KIEFER: And I've been
known to put just static images

00:42:47.010 --> 00:42:50.456
and movies, and view them in
gallery on the phone, just

00:42:50.456 --> 00:42:52.580
because holding it in your
hand kind of changes it.

00:42:52.580 --> 00:42:55.500
And so you can really get an
easy, fake interactive thing

00:42:55.500 --> 00:42:57.527
by pressing play,
and just kind of--

00:42:57.527 --> 00:42:58.360
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:00.610
NATHAN STRUE: Yep.

00:43:00.610 --> 00:43:03.960
AUDIENCE: Hi, I had a question
about creating cross platform

00:43:03.960 --> 00:43:04.565
mobile apps.

00:43:07.710 --> 00:43:10.860
Let's say you're working on
Android with new material

00:43:10.860 --> 00:43:14.110
design, and you're
also working on iOS.

00:43:14.110 --> 00:43:16.600
Both sort of have
similar design paradigms

00:43:16.600 --> 00:43:18.900
whenever you sort
of look at depth.

00:43:18.900 --> 00:43:22.060
IOS accomplishes that blur,
whereas material design does it

00:43:22.060 --> 00:43:24.410
with subtle shadows.

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:26.770
So my question is
whenever you're

00:43:26.770 --> 00:43:28.710
creating an app
for both platforms,

00:43:28.710 --> 00:43:32.600
do you conform to
the design paradigms

00:43:32.600 --> 00:43:34.820
of the specific platform?

00:43:34.820 --> 00:43:40.070
Or should you try to just create
one single cohesive design

00:43:40.070 --> 00:43:42.636
across both versions
of your app?

00:43:42.636 --> 00:43:46.290
NATHAN STRUE: Sure, that's
a very good question.

00:43:46.290 --> 00:43:48.150
I don't think there's
a direct answer.

00:43:48.150 --> 00:43:51.070
There's certain
platform paradigms

00:43:51.070 --> 00:43:55.280
that are very core
to a user experience.

00:43:55.280 --> 00:44:03.910
There are some that for
instance, a good example is

00:44:03.910 --> 00:44:08.200
when we were developing
music on iOS,

00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:11.100
we really felt our
interaction of our tab model

00:44:11.100 --> 00:44:12.460
was super successful.

00:44:12.460 --> 00:44:15.399
And iOS's tab
platform didn't really

00:44:15.399 --> 00:44:16.940
let us do the things
we wanted to do.

00:44:16.940 --> 00:44:20.310
So that was something where
we took a pattern from Android

00:44:20.310 --> 00:44:22.520
and applied it to iOS.

00:44:22.520 --> 00:44:24.730
There's other areas, I
can't think of anything

00:44:24.730 --> 00:44:26.690
off the top of my
head, but where

00:44:26.690 --> 00:44:29.110
you do you want to conform
to the platform standards.

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:31.059
TADDEO ZACCHINI: Oh,
well like the back button

00:44:31.059 --> 00:44:32.350
in the ActionWare, for example.

00:44:32.350 --> 00:44:32.910
That's typical.

00:44:32.910 --> 00:44:33.701
NATHAN STRUE: Sure.

00:44:33.701 --> 00:44:36.680
TADDEO ZACCHINI: So you may
align your visual design

00:44:36.680 --> 00:44:39.230
to this material
design guidelines.

00:44:39.230 --> 00:44:42.860
But the interaction and some
of the key elements of the UI

00:44:42.860 --> 00:44:46.614
can still be platform
based, like the back button.

00:44:46.614 --> 00:44:49.030
NATHAN STRUE: You want to make
sure to respect your user's

00:44:49.030 --> 00:44:49.900
comfort.

00:44:49.900 --> 00:44:51.550
And if they've spent
all of their time

00:44:51.550 --> 00:44:53.525
on a specific platform.

00:44:53.525 --> 00:44:55.650
There's going to be certain
platform paradigms that

00:44:55.650 --> 00:44:57.740
makes sense to adopt.

00:44:57.740 --> 00:45:02.330
So there's not a good
definitive answer there.

00:45:02.330 --> 00:45:05.370
I would say try to be as
consistent with the product

00:45:05.370 --> 00:45:09.490
across all platforms as possible
in the major structural and

00:45:09.490 --> 00:45:14.570
component elements, but
respect the platform paradigm.

00:45:14.570 --> 00:45:18.300
WILL KIEFER: And there's some
platform sort of interactions

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:21.690
that are not necessarily
tied to the model.

00:45:21.690 --> 00:45:24.107
Like the edge swipe
on iOS to go back.

00:45:24.107 --> 00:45:26.190
You can support that without
changing your design.

00:45:26.190 --> 00:45:27.520
But unfortunately,
we're out of time.

00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:29.020
So I really thank
you guys again.

00:45:29.020 --> 00:45:31.500
You can come grab us afterwards
if you have more questions.

00:45:31.500 --> 00:45:31.930
NATHAN STRUE: Thanks, everyone.

